nilworth, Warwickshire, England. His father was a mercenary in the Netherlands, and he himself became a cadet in the Prince of Orange's guards. In 1630 he emigrated to Boston, MA, where he was appointed captain of militia. In 1664–65 he played a significant role in helping to bring the Dutch colony of New Netherland under English control."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":3,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":23,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Anna Underhill was born in 1597, in Hail Weston, Huntingdonshire, England, her father, Rogeri Underhill, was 17 and her mother, Thomasine Frevile, was 17. She married John Payne on 3 August 1620, in Hail Weston, Huntingdonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1621, in England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1597–1621":"1597–1621","1595–1635":"1595–1635","1597–1650":"1597–1650","1621–1668":"1621–1668","1625–1682":"1625–1682","1580–1680":"1580–1680","1580–1641":"1580–1641","1682":"1682","1680":"1680","1580":"1580","3 August 1620":"3. august 1620","1668":"1668","1635":"1635","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1597":"1597","1641":"1641","1650":"1650","1595":"1595","22 Nov 1597":"22. november 1597","1625":"1625","Hail Weston, Huntingdonshire, England":"Hail Weston, Huntingdonshire, England","Moulton, Northamptonshire, England":"Moulton, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1597–1621":"1597–1621","1595–1635":"1595–1635","1597–1650":"1597–1650","1621–1668":"1621–1668","1625–1682":"1625–1682","1580–1680":"1580–1680","1580–1641":"1580–1641","1682":"1682","1680":"1680","1580":"1580","3 August 1620":"3. elokuuta 1620","1668":"1668","1635":"1635","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1597":"1597","1641":"1641","1650":"1650","1595":"1595","22 Nov 1597":"22. m